# Task boundaries and new chats

There's no tool to clear context or start a new chat yourself, that's the user's action. Instead of staying silent, notice the boundary yourself and raise it as an explicit choice via AskUserQuestion, without waiting to be asked.

What a hook now enforces mechanically. Context size, a number from the transcript, is checked by the `context-check.sh` Stop hook (registered in `~/.claude/settings.json`), the same way `route-gate` forces a conscious model choice. It reads the summed usage of the last main-session assistant message (input + cache_creation + cache_read + output, subagent/sidechain entries excluded), tracks it per model so a `/model` switch does not corrupt the count, and on crossing a threshold blocks the response from ending (`decision:block`, exit 2). Thresholds derive from the model's window (default 1M in this environment, override with `CONTEXT_CHECK_WINDOW`):

- Soft mark, 55% of the window (about 550k at 1M). An advisory nudge, enforced as text, not a forced tool call. In one line you either raise the checkpoint with AskUserQuestion, or, if this is focused continuous work that needs the accumulated history (the documented exception), say so and continue. The exception is yours to invoke here.
- Hard mark, 88% of the window (about 880k, before the harness force-compacts near ~99%). The exception no longer applies. The hook demands you call AskUserQuestion now, before any other text, and re-fires on every Stop until a real AskUserQuestion appears in the transcript. Only if the tool is genuinely unavailable that turn do you fall back to a caps-locked text warning listing the three options.

What stays your judgment, invisible to the hook: whether the task is closed and the next request is unrelated, whether the remaining work needs the old history, and the focused-work exception itself. The hook computes only the numeric half and hands the decision back to you.

Anti-nag: after a soft fire the hook stays quiet until context grows another ~15% of the window (about 150k at 1M; per-session, per-model state in `~/.claude/hooks/state/<session_id>.context.json`). After a hard checkpoint is raised and answered it goes quiet until the same further growth, which near the ceiling usually means auto-compaction handles it. Auto-compaction or `/clear` lowers the count and re-arms the track. Instant off switch: `touch ~/.claude/hooks/context-check.disabled`, back on with `rm`.

Briefly describe the situation in text before asking. The question offers three options:
- **Handoff prompt for a new chat** — generate a self-contained handoff immediately (goal and state, what's done and verified, changed files with paths, decisions made and why, rejected dead ends, exact next steps) entirely inside one standard fenced code block with its copy button, same as CD prompts; the user opens a new chat and pastes it with one click.
- **Clear context, stay here** — you can't do this yourself, just tell them the command to clear the current chat.
- **Keep going** — no change.

# Agent routing (kernel)

Details live in the model-routing skill; load it before the first agent spawn in a task. This kernel applies even when the skill is not loaded.

1. Every Agent/Task call carries an explicit model parameter (haiku/sonnet/opus/fable/inherit). The built-in Explore and general-purpose agents silently inherit the expensive session model without it: that is a routing miss, not a neutral default. Use inherit only deliberately, with a one-line reason.
2. Search, recon, grep sweeps, targeted lookups: Explore or general-purpose with model: haiku. Wide search is not forbidden, split it into parallel haiku spawns by directory. Fully specified mechanics (renames, cleanups, boilerplate, doc edits): the cheap agent.
3. Self-contained implementation (features, scoped refactors, localizations, UI edits from an approved decision, build/run checks): the dev agent, the default executor for code. Known-hard work (races, schema and public-API migrations, adversarial reviews, staged sync verification): straight to hard, no prior failures required.
4. Inline work in the main session is the exception and needs a named reason from the closed list in the skill (owner interaction within the same exchange; an edit shorter than the spawn prompt; an explicit user request). Unresolved fork in the task: ask in chat, then spawn with the decision baked into the prompt instead of keeping the task yourself.
5. If the route-gate hook is installed (see README): Explore without a model is auto-routed to haiku, general-purpose without a model is denied until a model is named, a super spawn raises a native confirmation dialog. Its messages are routing checkpoints, not errors. Off switch: `touch ~/.claude/hooks/route-gate.disabled`.
6. Never delegate: secrets, signing, notarization, store submissions; git push and destructive git; the overwrite act of canon syncs; personal legal, tax, and medical matters; interactive flows with mid-task confirmations.

# Tokens and models: on demand only

There's no forced report after every reply. That mechanism was removed on 2026-07-21: even with a counter-example written into this file, the model kept re-triggering the same bug (appending a report line from habit before the hook actually fired, then the hook firing for real and forcing a second, identical one). A text-only fix didn't hold reliably, and hardening the hook further wasn't judged worth it. `~/.claude/hooks/token-report.sh` is deleted, unregistered from `~/.claude/settings.json`.

Show token and model numbers only when asked, with two commands: `/usage-report` (what actually ran this session, model by model, real numbers from the transcript) and `/routing-status` (the same, plus the routing table from `route-gate.log`, an independent check that the routing skill is actually working). Neither appears on its own at the end of a reply, and neither forces anything.
